author: Rurfs

text:
@Rurfs A woman protagonist who takes advantage of a woman's strength in a comedic manner to rescue her 'strong man' is totally negative.
Women have emotions. In many cases, those emotions are stronger than men's. it is not a weakness, but a genetic strength that allows women increased artistic passion or better empathy in certain jobs. The game shows a women taking advantage of her emotions to overcome obstacles.
The joke is that in the end it's a fucking game, one that again portrays Peach comically and positively, and no one can just press a button and swap emotions, or do any of the shit peach does in the game. 
With this, we can take away that 'Feminists' want women to be portrayed exactly like men, the emotionless physical labor machine they fostered, with no room for silly things like women being strong in their own ways, or being capable. Who cares if Peach is saving Mario? She's not being a man while doing it! Meanwhile if they DID make her burly and a headstomping machine, stronger than Mario, they'd level accusations of it being a 'man with boobs'.
Fulla shit, it is, and they wonder why so few games cater to their whims.

author: Dessa

text: @Dessa I've never once perceived "feminazi" to mean "feminist". Feminism is a good, healthy thing for our culture to embrace as women are truly capable of anything a man is. A "feminazi" is something I've always perceived as an oversensitive individual (gets offended with the drop of a hat, actively searches for things to find offensive) with an inflated ego and confused ideas about what equality is. While vocal, this group of people is really small in comparison to actual feminists, I think. I believe it's not productive to assume that others are lumping the two groups together, that's like saying the tea party and all republicans are the same entity.
